<DOC><DOCNO> AP890428-0033 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0249EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Pope-Africa     04-28 0155</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Pope-Africa,0159</SECOND><HEAD>Pope Departs For Madagascar To Begin 9-Day African Tour</HEAD><DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Pope John Paul II left Friday on his fifth Africantour for Madagascar, where violent protests against the governmentof President Didier Ratsiraka the last week have left five peopledead.   The pontiff's special Alitalia Boeing 747 left Rome's Leonardoda Vinci Airport at 8 a.m. for a nine-hour flight to Madagascar'scapital, Antananarivo.   It is the first stop on a nine-day trip that also will take thepope to the French island of Reunion in the Indian Ocean, and toZambia and Malawi. It is the 41st foreign pilgrimage of John Paul's10{-year papacy.   In all, the pope will deliver 36 speeches and travel 13,500miles during his trip. He is scheduled to return to Rome on May 6.   Africa is the continent where Roman Catholicism is growingfastest. The Vatican says it has 75 million followers in Africa.</TEXT></DOC>